      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Originalism is fundamentally rooted in the idea that the Constitution is a fixed document, not a living text that can be endlessly reinterpreted by judges. Proponents argue that the Founders intended a specific meaning for the text at the time it was ratified, and judges must adhere to that original public meaning. This approach prevents unelected judges from imposing their personal, modern policy preferences onto the law. Therefore, originalism ensures stability and fidelity to the democratic will expressed at the nation's founding.",
